# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tsmc-process-node
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] In semiconductor manufacturing, the International Roadmap for Devices and Systems defines the **"5 nm" process** as the MOSFET technology node following the "7 nm" node.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] In 2020, Samsung and TSMC entered volume production of "5 nm" chips, manufactured for companies including Apple, Huawei, Mediatek, Qualcomm and Marvell.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] The term "5 nm" does not indicate that any physical feature (such as gate length, metal pitch or gate pitch) of the transistors is five nanometers in size.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] Historically, the number used in the name of a technology node represented the gate length, but it started deviating from the actual length to smaller numbers (by Intel) around 2011.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] According to the projections contained in the 2021 update of the International Roadmap for Devices and Systems published by IEEE Standards Association Industry Connection, the 5 nm node is expected to have a gate length of 18 nm, a contacted gate pitch of 51 nm, and a tightest metal pitch of 30 nm.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] Quantum tunnelling effects through the gate oxide layer on "7 nm" and "5 nm" transistors became increasingly difficult to manage using existing semiconductor processes.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] Single-transistor devices below 7 nm were first demonstrated by researchers in the early 2000s.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] In 2002, an IBM research team including Bruce Doris, Omer Dokumaci, Meikei Ieong and Anda Mocuta fabricated a 6-nanometre silicon-on-insulator (SOI) MOSFET.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] In 2003, a Japanese research team at NEC, led by Hitoshi Wakabayashi and Shigeharu Yamagami, fabricated the first 5 nm MOSFET.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] In 2015, IMEC and Cadence fabricated 5 nm test chips.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] The fabricated test chips were not fully functional devices, but rather are to evaluate patterning of interconnect layers.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] In 2015, Intel described a lateral nanowire (or gate-all-around) FET concept for the "5 nm" node.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] In 2017, IBM revealed that it had created "5 nm" silicon chips, using silicon nanosheets in a *gate-all-around* configuration (GAAFET), a break from the usual FinFET design.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] The GAAFET transistors used had 3 nanosheets stacked on top of each other, covered in their entirety by the same gate, just like FinFETs usually have several physical fins side by side that are electrically a single unit and are covered in their entirety by the same gate.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] IBM's chip measured 50 mm2 and had 600 million transistors per mm2, for a total of 30 billion transistors (1667 nm2 per transistor or 41 nm actual transistor spacing).
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] In April 2019, Samsung Electronics announced they had been offering their "5 nm" process (5LPE) tools to their customers since 2018 Q4.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] In April 2019, TSMC announced that their "5 nm" process (CLN5FF, N5) had begun risk production, and that full chip design specifications were now available to potential customers.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] The N5 process can use EUVL on up to 14 layers, compared to only 5 or 4 layers in N6 and N7++.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] For the expected 28 nm minimum metal pitch, SALELE is the proposed best patterning method.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] For their "5 nm" process, Samsung started process defect mitigation by automated check and fix, due to occurrence of stochastic (random) defects in the metal and via layers.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] In October 2019, TSMC reportedly started sampling 5 nm A14 processors for Apple.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] At the 2020 IEEE IEDM conference, TSMC reported their 5 nm process had 1.84x higher density than their 7 nm process.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] At IEDM 2019, TSMC revealed two versions of 5 nm, a DUV version with a 5.5-track cell, and an (official) EUV version with a 6-track cell.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] In December 2019, TSMC announced an average yield of approximately 80%, with a peak yield per wafer of over 90% for their "5 nm" test chips with a die size of 17.92 mm2.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] In mid 2020 TSMC claimed its (N5) "5 nm" process offered 1.8x the density of its "7 nm" N7 process, with 15% speed improvement or 30% lower power consumption; an improved sub-version (N5P or N4) was claimed to improve on N5 with +5% speed or -10% power.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] On 13 October 2020, Apple announced a new iPhone 12 lineup using the A14.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] Together with the Huawei Mate 40 lineup using the HiSilicon Kirin 9000, the A14 and Kirin 9000 were the first devices to be commercialized on TSMC's "5 nm" node.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] Later, on 10 November 2020, Apple also revealed three new Mac models using the Apple M1, another 5 nm chip.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] According to Semianalysis, the A14 processor has a transistor density of 134 million transistors per mm2.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] In October 2021, TSMC introduced a new member of its "5 nm" process family: N4P.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] Compared to N5, the node offered 11% higher performance (6% higher vs N4), 22% higher power efficiency, 6% higher transistor density and lower mask count.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] TSMC expected first tapeouts by the second half of 2022.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] In December 2021, TSMC announced a new member of its "5 nm" process family designed for HPC applications: N4X.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] The process featured optimized transistor design and structures, reduced resistance and capacitance of targeted metal layers and high-density MiM capacitors.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] The process was expected at that time to offer up to 15% higher performance vs N5 (or up to 4% vs N4P) at 1.2 V and supply voltage in excess of 1.2 V.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] TSMC, at that time, said that they expected N4X to enter risk production by the first half of 2023.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] Intel's first product to be fabbed on Intel 4 was Meteor Lake, powered on in Q2 2022 and scheduled for shipping in 2023.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] Intel 4 has contacted gate pitch of 50 nm, both fin and minimum metal pitch of 30 nm, and library height of 240 nm.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] Metal-insulator-metal capacitance was increased to 376 fF/μm², roughly 2x compared to Intel 7.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] The process was optimized for HPC applications and supported voltage from <0.65 V to >1.3 V.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] WikiChip's transistor density estimate for Intel 4 was 123.4 Mtr./mm², 2.04x from 60.5 Mtr./mm² for Intel 7.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] However, high-density SRAM cell had scaled only by 0.77x (from 0.0312 to 0.024 μm²) and high-performance cell by 0.68x (from 0.0441 to 0.03 μm²) compared to Intel 7.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] On 27 September 2022, AMD officially launched their Ryzen 7000 series of central processing units, based on the TSMC N5 process and Zen 4 microarchitecture.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] Zen 4 marked the first utilization of the 5 nm process for x86-based desktop processors.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] In December 2022 AMD also launched the Radeon RX 7000 series of graphics processing units based on RDNA 3, which also used the TSMC N5 process.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] On 26 August 2024 IBM introduced their Telum II processor, based on Samsung's 5 nm process.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] Transistor gate pitch is also referred to as CPP (contacted poly pitch) and interconnect pitch is also referred to as MMP (minimum metal pitch).
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] "3 nm" is the usual term for the next node after "5 nm".
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] As of 2023, TSMC has started producing chips for select customers, while Samsung and Intel have plans for 2024.
[src:tsmc-process-node/5-nm-process] "3.5 nm" has also been given as a name for the first node beyond "5 nm".
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] In semiconductor manufacturing, the **"7 nm" process** is a term for the MOSFET technology node following the "10 nm" node, defined by the International Roadmap for Devices and Systems (IRDS), which was preceded by the International Technology Roadmap for Semiconductors (ITRS).
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] It is based on FinFET (fin field-effect transistor) technology, a type of multi-gate MOSFET technology.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] The 2021 IRDS Lithography standard is a retrospective document, as the first volume production of a "7 nm" branded process was in 2016 with Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company's (TSMC) production of 256Mbit SRAM memory chips using a "7nm" process called N7.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Samsung started mass production of their "7nm" process (7LPP) devices in 2018.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Since at least 1997, the length scale of a process node has not referred to any particular dimension on the integrated circuits, such as gate length, metal pitch, or gate pitch, as new lithography processes no longer uniformly shrank all features on a chip.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] By the late 2010s, the length scale had become a commercial name that indicated a new generation of process technologies, without any relation to physical properties.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Previous ITRS and IRDS standards had insufficient guidance on process node naming conventions to address the widely varying dimensions on a chip, leading to a divergence between how foundries branded their lithography and the actual dimensions their process nodes achieved.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] The first mainstream "7nm" mobile processor intended for mass market use, the Apple A12 Bionic, was announced at Apple's September 2018 event.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Although Huawei announced its own "7nm" processor before the Apple A12 Bionic, the Kirin 980 on August 31, 2018, the Apple A12 Bionic was released for public, mass market use to consumers before the Kirin 980.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] In 2019, AMD released their "Rome" (EPYC 2) processors for servers and datacenters, which are based on TSMC's N7 node and feature up to 64 cores and 128 threads.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] They also released their "Matisse" consumer desktop processors with up to 16 cores and 32 threads.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] However, the I/O die on the Rome multi-chip module (MCM) is fabricated with the GlobalFoundries' 14 nm (14HP) process, while the Matisse's I/O die uses the GlobalFoundries' "12nm" (12LP+) process.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] The Radeon RX 5000 series is also based on TSMC's N7 process.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] In the early 2000s, researchers began demonstrating 7 nm level MOSFETs, with an IBM team including Bruce Doris, Omer Dokumaci, Meikei Ieong, and Anda Mocuta successfully fabricating a 6 nm silicon-on-insulator (SOI) MOSFET.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Shortly after, in 2003, NEC's researchers Hitoshi Wakabayashi and Shigeharu Yamagami advanced further by fabricating a 5 nm MOSFET.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] In July 2015, IBM announced that they had built the first functional transistors with "7nm" technology, using a silicon-germanium process.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] This cumulated in TSMC starting volume of 7 nm production in 2018.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] In 2015, Intel expected that at the 7 nm node, III–V semiconductors would have to be used in transistors, signaling a shift away from silicon.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] In April 2016, TSMC announced that "7nm" trial production would begin in the first half of 2017.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] In April 2017, TSMC began risk production of 256Mbit SRAM memory chips using a "7nm" (N7FF+) process, with extreme ultraviolet lithography (EUV).
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] TSMC's "7nm" production plans, as of early 2017, was to use deep ultraviolet (DUV) immersion lithography initially on this process node (N7FF), and transition from risk to commercial volume manufacturing from Q2 2017 to Q2 2018.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Also, their later generation "7nm" (N7FF+) production was planned to use EUV multiple patterning and have an estimated transition from risk to volume manufacturing between 2018 and 2019.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] In September 2016, GlobalFoundries announced trial production in the second half of 2017 and risk production in early 2018, with test chips already running.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] In February 2017, Intel announced Fab 42 in Chandler, Arizona, which was according to press releases at that time expected to produce microprocessors using a "7nm" (Intel 4) manufacturing process.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] The company had not, at that time, published any expected values for feature lengths at this process node.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] In April 2018, TSMC announced volume production of "7nm" (CLN7FF, N7) chips.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] In June 2018, the company announced mass production ramp up.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] In May 2018, Samsung announced production of "7nm" (7LPP) chips for later that year.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] ASML Holding NV is their main supplier of EUV lithography machines.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] In August 2018, GlobalFoundries announced it was stopping development of "7nm" chips, citing cost.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] On October 28, 2018, Samsung announced their second generation "7nm" process (7LPP) had entered risk production and was at that time expected to have entered mass production by 2019.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] On January 17, 2019, for the Q4 2018 earnings call, TSMC mentioned that different customers would have "different flavors" of second generation "7nm".
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] On April 16, 2019, TSMC announced their "6nm" process called (CLN6FF, N6), which was, according to a press release made on April 16, 2019, at that time expected to have been in mass products from 2021.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] N6 was at that time expected to have used EUVL in up to 5 layers, compared to up to 4 layers in their N7+ process.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] On July 28, 2019, TSMC announced their second gen "7nm" process called N7P, which was projected to have been DUV-based like their N7 process.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Since N7P was fully IP-compatible with the original "7nm", while N7+ (which uses EUV) was not, N7+ (announced earlier as "7nm+") was to have been a separate process from "7nm".
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] N6 ("6nm"), another EUV-based process, was at that time planned to have been released later than even TSMC's "5nm" (N5) process, with the IP-compatibility with N7.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] At their Q1 2019 earnings call, TSMC reiterated their Q4 2018 statement that N7+ was at that time expected to have generated less than $1 billion TWD in revenue in 2019.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] On October 5, 2019, AMD announced their EPYC Roadmap, featuring Milan chips built using TSMC's N7+ process.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] On October 7, 2019, TSMC announced they had started delivering N7+ products to market in high volume.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] On July 26, 2021, Intel announced their new manufacturing roadmap, renaming all of their future process nodes.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Intel's "10nm" Enhanced SuperFin (10ESF), which was roughly equivalent to TSMC's N7 process, would thenceforth be known as "Intel 7", while their earlier "7nm" process would erstwhile be called "Intel 4".
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] As a result, Intel's first processors based on Intel 7 were at that time planned to have started shipping by the second half of 2022, whereas Intel announced earlier that they were planning to have launched "7nm" processors in 2023.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] In June 2018, AMD announced 7 nm Radeon Instinct GPUs launching in the second half of 2018.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] In August 2018, the company confirmed the release of the GPUs.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] On August 21, 2018, Huawei announced their HiSilicon Kirin 980 SoC to be used in their Huawei Mate 20 and Mate 20 Pro built using TSMC's 7 nm (N7) process.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] On September 12, 2018, Apple announced their A12 Bionic chip used in iPhone XS and iPhone XR built using TSMC's 7 nm (N7) process.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] The A12 processor became the first 7 nm chip for mass market use as it released before the Huawei Mate 20.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] On October 30, 2018, Apple announced their A12X Bionic chip used in iPad Pro built using TSMC's 7 nm (N7) process.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] On December 4, 2018, Qualcomm announced their Snapdragon 855 and 8cx built using TSMC's 7 nm (N7) process.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] The first mass product featuring the Snapdragon 855 was the Lenovo Z5 Pro GT, which was announced on December 18, 2018.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] On May 29, 2019, MediaTek announced their 5G SoC built using a TSMC 7 nm process.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] On July 7, 2019, AMD officially launched their Ryzen 3000 series of central processing units, based on the TSMC 7 nm process and Zen 2 microarchitecture.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] On August 6, 2019, Samsung announced their Exynos 9825 SoC, the first chip built using their 7LPP process.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] The Exynos 9825 is the first mass market chip built featuring EUVL.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] On September 6, 2019, Huawei announced their HiSilicon Kirin 990 4G & 990 5G SoCs, built using TSMC's N7 and N7+ processes.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] On September 10, 2019, Apple announced their A13 Bionic chip used in iPhone 11 and iPhone 11 Pro built using TSMC's 2nd gen N7P process.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] 7 nm (N7 nodes) manufacturing made up 36% of TSMC's revenue in the second quarter of 2020.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] On August 17, 2020, IBM announced their Power10 processor.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] On July 26, 2021, Intel announced that their Alder Lake processors would be manufactured using their newly rebranded "Intel 7" process, previously known as "10nm Enhanced SuperFin".
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] These processors were, at that time, expected based on press releases to have been planned to have been released in the second half of 2021.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] The company earlier confirmed a 7 nm, now called "Intel 4", microprocessor family called Meteor Lake to be released in 2023.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] The "7nm" foundry node is expected to utilize any of or a combination of the following patterning technologies: pitch splitting, self-aligned patterning, and EUV lithography.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Each of these technologies carries significant challenges in critical dimension (CD) control as well as pattern placement, all involving neighboring features.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Pitch splitting involves splitting features that are too close together onto different masks, which are exposed successively, followed by litho-etch processing.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Due to the use of different exposures, there is always the risk of overlay error between the two exposures, as well as different CDs resulting from the different exposures.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Spacer patterning involves depositing a layer onto pre-patterned features, then etching back to form spacers on the sidewalls of those features, referred to as core features.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] After removing the core features, the spacers are used as an etch mask to define trenches in the underlying layer.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] While the spacer CD control is generally excellent, the trench CD may fall into one of two populations, due to the two possibilities of being located where a core feature was located or in the remaining gap.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Generally, pitch = core CD + gap CD + 2 * spacer CD, but this does not guarantee core CD = gap CD.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] For FEOL features like gate or active area isolation (e.g. fins), the trench CD is not as critical as the spacer-defined CD, in which case, spacer patterning is actually the preferred patterning approach.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] When self-aligned quadruple patterning (SAQP) is used, there is a second spacer that is utilized, replacing the first one.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] In this case, the core CD is replaced by core CD – 2* 2nd spacer CD, and the gap CD is replaced by gap CD – 2 * 2nd spacer CD.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Thus, some feature dimensions are strictly defined by the second spacer CD, while the remaining feature dimensions are defined by the core CD, core pitch, and first and second spacer CD's.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] The core CD and core pitch are defined by conventional lithography, while the spacer CDs are independent of lithography.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] This is actually expected to have less variation than pitch splitting, where an additional exposure defines its own CD, both directly and through overlay.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Spacer-defined lines also require cutting.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] The cut spots may shift at exposure, resulting in distorted line ends or intrusions into adjacent lines.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Self-aligned litho-etch-litho-etch (SALELE) has been implemented for "7nm" BEOL patterning.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Extreme ultraviolet lithography (also known as ***EUV*** or ***EUVL***) is capable of resolving features below 20 nm in conventional lithography style.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] However, the 3D reflective nature of the EUV mask results in new anomalies in the imaging.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] One particular nuisance is the two-bar effect, where a pair of identical bar-shaped features do not focus identically.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] One feature is essentially in the 'shadow' of the other.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Consequently, the two features generally have different CDs which change through focus, and these features also shift position through focus.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] This effect may be similar to what may be encountered with pitch splitting.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] A related issue is the difference of best focus among features of different pitches.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] EUV also has issues with reliably printing all features in a large population; some contacts may be completely missing or lines bridged.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] These are known as stochastic printing failures.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] The defect level is on the order of 1K/mm2.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] The tip-to-tip gap is hard to control for EUV, largely due to the illumination constraint.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] A separate exposure(s) for cutting lines is preferred.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Attenuated phase shift masks have been used in production for 90 nm node for adequate focus windows for arbitrarily pitched contacts with the ArF laser wavelength (193 nm), whereas this resolution enhancement is not available for EUV.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] At 2021 SPIE's EUV Lithography conference, it was reported by a TSMC customer that EUV contact yield was comparable to immersion multipatterning yield.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Due to these challenges, "7nm" poses unprecedented patterning difficulty in the back end of line (BEOL).
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] The previous high-volume, long-lived foundry node (Samsung "10nm", TSMC "16nm") used pitch splitting for the tighter pitch metal layers.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Due to the immersion tools being faster presently, multipatterning is still used on most layers.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] On the layers requiring immersion quad-patterning, the layer completion throughput by EUV is comparable.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] On the other layers, immersion would be more productive at completing the layer even with multipatterning.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] The "7nm" metal patterning currently practiced by TSMC involves self-aligned double patterning (SADP) lines with cuts inserted within a cell on a separate mask as needed to reduce cell height.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] However, self-aligned quad patterning (SAQP) is used to form the fin, the most important factor to performance.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Design rule checks also allow via multi-patterning to be avoided, and provide enough clearances for cuts that only one cut mask is needed.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Since EUV implementation at "7nm" is still limited, multipatterning still plays an important part in cost and yield; EUV adds extra considerations.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] The resolution for most critical layers is still determined by multiple patterning.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] For example, for Samsung's "7nm", even with EUV single-patterned 36 nm pitch layers, 44 nm pitch layers would still be quadruple patterned.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] GlobalFoundries' "7nm" 7LP (Leading Performance) process would have offered 40% higher performance or 60%+ lower power with a 2x scaling in density and at a 30–45 + % lower cost per die over its "14nm" process.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] The Contacted Poly Pitch (CPP) would have been 56 nm and the Minimum Metal Pitch (MMP) would have been 40 nm, produced with Self-Aligned Double Patterning (SADP).
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] A 6T SRAM cell would have been 0.269 square microns in size.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] GlobalFoundries planned to eventually use EUV lithography in an improved process called 7LP+.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] GlobalFoundries later stopped all "7nm" and beyond process development.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Intel's new "Intel 7" process, previously known as "10nm Enhanced SuperFin" (10ESF), is based on its previous "10nm" node.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] The node will feature a 10–15% increase in performance per watt.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Meanwhile, their old "7nm" process, now called "Intel 4", was at that time expected to have been released in 2023.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] Few details about the "Intel 4" node had at that time been made public, although its transistor density had at that time been estimated to be at least 202 million transistors per square millimeter.
[src:tsmc-process-node/7-nm-process] As of 2020, Intel had been experiencing problems with its "Intel 4" process to the point of outsourcing production of its Ponte Vecchio GPUs.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] The **foundry model** is a microelectronics engineering and manufacturing business model consisting of a semiconductor fabrication plant, or foundry, and an integrated circuit design operation, each belonging to separate companies or subsidiaries.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] It was first conceived by Morris Chang, the founder of the Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company Limited (TSMC).
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Integrated device manufacturers (IDMs) design and manufacture integrated circuits.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Many companies, known as fabless semiconductor companies, only design devices; merchant or pure play foundries only manufacture devices for other companies, without designing them.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Examples of IDMs are Intel, Samsung, and Texas Instruments, examples of pure play foundries are GlobalFoundries, TSMC, and UMC, and examples of fabless companies are AMD, Nvidia, and Qualcomm.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Integrated circuit production facilities are expensive to build and maintain.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Unless they can be kept at nearly full use, they will become a drain on the finances of the company that owns them.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] The foundry model uses two methods to avoid these costs: fabless companies avoid costs by not owning such facilities.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Merchant foundries, on the other hand, find work from the worldwide pool of fabless companies, through careful scheduling, pricing, and contracting, keep their plants in full use.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Companies that both designed and produced the devices were originally responsible for manufacturing microelectronic devices.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] These manufacturers were involved in both the research and development of manufacturing processes and the research and development of microcircuit design.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] The separation of design and fabrication became known as the foundry model, with fabless manufacturing outsourcing to semiconductor foundries.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Fabless semiconductor companies do not have any semiconductor fabrication capability, instead contracting with a merchant foundry for fabrication.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] The fabless company concentrates on the research and development of an IC-product; the foundry concentrates on manufacturing and testing the physical product.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] If the foundry does not have any semiconductor design capability, it is a pure-play semiconductor foundry.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] An absolute separation into fabless and foundry companies is not necessary.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Many companies continue to exist that perform both operations and benefit from the close coupling of their skills.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Some companies manufacture some of their own designs and contract out to have others manufactured or designed, in cases where they see value or seek special skills.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] The foundry model is a business model that seeks to optimize productivity.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] The very first merchant foundries were part of the MOSIS service.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] The MOSIS service gave limited production access to designers with limited means, such as students, university researchers, and engineers at small startups.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] The designer submitted designs, and these submissions were manufactured with the commercial company's extra capacity.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Manufacturers could insert some wafers for a MOSIS design into a collection of their own wafers when a processing step was compatible with both operations.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] The commercial company (serving as foundry) was already running the process, so they were effectively being paid by MOSIS for something they were already doing.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] A factory with excess capacity during slow periods could also run MOSIS designs to avoid having expensive capital equipment stand idle.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Under-use of an expensive manufacturing plant could lead to the financial ruin of the owner, so selling surplus wafer capacity was a way to maximize the fab's use.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Hence, economic factors created a climate where fab operators wanted to sell surplus wafer-manufacturing capacity and designers wanted to purchase manufacturing capacity rather than try to build it.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Although MOSIS opened the doors to some fabless customers, earning additional revenue for the foundry and providing inexpensive service to the customer, running a business around MOSIS production was difficult.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] The merchant foundries sold wafer capacity on a surplus basis, as a secondary business activity.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Services to the customers were secondary to the commercial business, with little guarantee of support.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] The choice of merchant dictated the design, development flow, and available techniques to the fabless customer.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Merchant foundries might require proprietary and non-portable preparation steps.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Foundries concerned with protecting what they considered trade secrets of their methodologies might only be willing to release data to designers after an onerous nondisclosure procedure.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] In 1987, the world's first dedicated merchant foundry opened its doors: Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company (TSMC).
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] The distinction of 'dedicated' is in reference to the typical merchant foundry of the era, whose primary business activity was building and selling of its own IC-products.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] The dedicated foundry offers several key advantages to its customers: first, it does not sell finished IC-products into the supply channel; thus a dedicated foundry will never compete directly with its fabless customers (obviating a common concern of fabless companies).
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Second, the dedicated foundry can scale production capacity to a customer's needs, offering low-quantity shuttle services in addition to full-scale production lines.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Finally, the dedicated foundry offers a "COT-flow" (customer owned tooling) based on industry-standard EDA systems, whereas many IDM merchants required its customers to use proprietary (non-portable) development tools.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] The COT advantage gave the customer complete control over the design process, from concept to final design.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] The cost to stay on the leading edge has steadily increased with each generation of chips.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] The financial strain is being felt by both large merchant foundries and their fabless customers.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] The cost of a new foundry exceeds $1 billion.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Many merchant foundries have entered into joint ventures with their competitors in an effort to split research and design expenditures and fab-maintenance expenses.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Chip design companies sometimes avoid other companies' patents simply by purchasing the products from a licensed foundry with broad cross-license agreements with the patent owner.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] Stolen design data is also a concern; data is rarely directly copied, because blatant copies are easily identified by distinctive features in the chip, placed there either for this purpose or as a byproduct of the design process.
[src:tsmc-process-node/foundry-model] However, the data including any procedure, process system, method of operation or concept may be sold to a competitor, who may save months or years of tedious reverse engineering.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] With the MPC arrangement, one chip is a combination of several designs and this combined chip is then repeated all over the wafer during the manufacturing.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] The MPC arrangement typically produces a roughly equal number of chip designs per wafer.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] With the MPW arrangement, different chip designs are aggregated on a wafer, with perhaps a different number of designs/projects per wafer.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] This is made possible by novel mask-making and exposure systems in photolithography during IC manufacturing.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] MPW builds upon the older MPC procedures and enables more effective support for different phases and needs of manufacturing volumes of different designs/projects.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] MPW arrangement support education, research of new circuit architectures and structures, prototyping, and even small-volume production.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] Worldwide, several MPW services are available from companies, semiconductor foundries and from government-supported institutions.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] Originally both MPC and MPW arrangements were introduced for integrated circuit (IC) education and research; some MPC/MPW services/gateways are aimed for non-commercial use only.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] Currently MPC/MPW services are effectively used for system on a chip integration.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] Selecting the right service platform at the prototyping phase ensures gradual scaling up production via MPW services taking into account the rules of the selected service.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] MPC/MPW arrangements have also been applied to microelectromechanical systems (MEMS), integrated photonics like photonics fabrication including also other materials than silicon like InP, flexible electronics, microfluidics and even chiplets.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] A refinement of MPW is multi-layer mask (MLM) arrangement, where a limited number of masks (e.g.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] 4) are changed during manufacturing at exposure phase.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] The rest of the masks are the same from the chip to chip on the whole wafer.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] Typically MLM approach is used for one wafer batch (consisting of several wafers depending on the fabrication line) and for one customer.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] By using MLM it is possible to get larger devices (even up to wafer size) or larger number of dies and wafers up to few batches typically.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] MLM is a smooth continuation from MPW production volumes upwards and therefore this may support also small/mid size volume production.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] Not all foundries support MLM arrangements.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] Due to the complexity of the technologies available and the need to run MPC/MPWs smoothly, following the rules, timing of the designs and use of suggested design tools are critical for leveraging the benefits of MPC/MPW services.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] However every service provider has its own practicalities including design data, die sizes, design rules, device models, design tools used, ready IP blocks available and timing etc.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] Turn around times and cost of MPC and MPW services depend on the manufacturing technology and designs/prototypes are typically available as bare dies or as packaged devices.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] Deliveries are typically untested, but in most of the cases the quality of the manufacturing process is guaranteed by the measurement results of process control monitor(s) (PCM) or similar.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] CMC Microsystems is a not-for-profit organization in Canada accelerating research and innovation in advanced technologies.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] Founded in 1984, CMC lowers barriers to designing, manufacturing, and testing prototypes in microelectronics, photonics, quantum, MEMS, and packaging.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] CMC technology platforms such as the ESP (Electronic Sensor Platform) jumpstart R&D projects, enabling engineers and scientists to achieve results sooner and at a lower cost.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] Annually, more than 700 research teams from companies and 100 academic institutions around the world access CMC's services and turn more than 400 designs into prototypes through its global network of manufacturers.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] This support enables 400 industrial collaborations and 1,000 trained HQP to join industry each year, and these relationships assist in the translation of academic research into outcomes—publications, patents, and commercialization.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] Muse Semiconductor was founded in 2018 by former eSilicon employees.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] The company name "Muse" is an informal acronym for MPW University SErvice.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] Muse focuses on serving the MPW needs of microelectronics researchers.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] Muse supports all TSMC technologies and offers an MPW service with a minimum area of 1mm^2 for some technologies.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] Muse is a member of the TSMC University FinFET Program.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] The first well known MPC service was MOSIS (Metal Oxide Silicon Implementation Service), established by DARPA as a technical and human infrastructure for VLSI.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] MOSIS began in 1981 after Lynn Conway organized the first VLSI System Design Course at MIT in 1978 and the course produced 'multi-university, multi-project chip-design demonstration' delivering devices to the course participants in 1979.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] The designs for the MPC were gathered using ARPANET.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] The technical background additionally to education was to develop and research in a cost effective way new computer architectures without limitations of standard components.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] MOSIS primarily services commercial users with MPW arrangement.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] MOSIS has ended their University Support Program.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] With MOSIS, designs are submitted for fabrication using either open (i.e., non-proprietary) VLSI layout design rules or vendor proprietary rules.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] Designs are pooled into common lots and run through the fabrication process at foundries.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] The completed chips (packaged or bare dies) are returned to customers.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] The first international silicon IC MPC service NORCHIP was established among four nordic countries (Denmark, Finland, Norway and Sweden) 1981 delivering first chips 1982.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] It was funded by Nordic Industrial Fund and R&D financing organisations from each participating country.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] Targets were training and to enhance cooperation between research and industry specifically in areas of analog and digital signal processing and power management Integration.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] Parallel with NORCHIP organised by same nordic countries there was Nordic GaAs program NOGAP 1986-1989, which produced modelling techniques for GaAs IC devices, and demonstrators of high speed digital and RF/analog MMICs.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] From 1989 to 1995 nordic universities, research institutes and small companies have been participating in european EUROCHIP and from 1995 on wards in EUROPRACTICE.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] CMP a French company working since 1981 started MPC operation with NMOS offering but expanding offering to CMOS and various other technologies.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] CMP was also the first official pan-continental MPC/MPW operation having link to MOSIS among other MPW arrangements globally.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] CMPs services have included variety of technologies including multi-chip modules (MCMs) suitable for the packaging of chiplets.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] BERCHIP MPC activity starting in 1994 was organised in Latin America.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] Numerous MPW services have been launched since 1994 worldwide.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] Tiny Tapeout is a multi project chip service that lowers the barrier to entry to chip design by using open source tools and PDKs.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] To reduce the cost of tapeout, up to 512 analog and digital designs are connected via a power-gated multiplexer.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] As of 2026 supported PDKs are Skywater's SKY130, IHP's SG13G2 and Global Foundries' GF180mcu.
[src:tsmc-process-node/multi-project-wafer-service] Tiny Tapeout schedules multiple tapeout opportunities per year.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] In the microelectronics industry, a **semiconductor fabrication plant**, also called a ***fab*** or a ***foundry***, is a factory where integrated circuits (ICs) are manufactured.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] The *cleanroom* is where all fabrication takes place and contains the machinery for integrated circuit production such as steppers and/or scanners for photolithography, etching, cleaning, and doping.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Prices for pieces of equipment for the processing of 300mm wafers range to upwards of $4 million each with a few pieces of equipment reaching as high as $340 million (e.g.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] A typical fab will have several hundred equipment items.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Semiconductor fabrication requires many expensive devices.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Estimates put the cost of building a new fab at over one billion U.S. dollars with values as high as tens of billions of dollars not being uncommon.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] For example, TSMC invested over $45 billion into a new fab for their 2nm process.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] A foundry model emerged in the 1990s: Companies owning fabs that produced their own designs were known as *integrated device manufacturers* (IDMs).
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Companies that outsourced manufacturing of their designs were termed *fabless semiconductor companies*.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Those foundries which did not create their own designs were called *pure-play semiconductor foundries*.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] In the cleanroom, the environment is controlled to eliminate all dust, since even a single speck can ruin a microcircuit, which has nanoscale features much smaller than dust particles.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] The clean room must also be damped against vibration to enable nanometer-scale alignment of photolithography machines and must be kept within narrow bands of temperature and humidity.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Vibration control may be achieved by using deep piles in the cleanroom's foundation that anchor the cleanroom to the bedrock, careful selection of the construction site, and/or using vibration dampers.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Controlling temperature and humidity is critical for minimizing static electricity.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Corona discharge sources can also be used to reduce static electricity.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Typically, an advance in chip-making technology requires a completely new fab to be built.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] In the past, the equipment to outfit a fab was not very expensive and there were a huge number of smaller fabs producing chips in small quantities.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] However, the cost of the most up-to-date equipment has since grown to the point where a new fab can cost several billion dollars.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Another side effect of the cost has been the challenge to make use of older fabs.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] For many companies these older fabs are useful for producing designs for unique markets, such as embedded processors, flash memory, and microcontrollers.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] However, for companies with more limited product lines, it is often best to either rent out the fab, or close it entirely.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] This is due to the tendency of the cost of upgrading an existing fab to produce devices requiring newer technology to exceed the cost of a completely new fab.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] There has been a trend to produce ever larger wafers; each process step is being performed on more and more chips at once.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] The goal is to spread production costs (chemicals, fab time) over a larger number of sale-able chips.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] It is impossible (or at least impracticable) to retrofit machinery to handle larger wafers.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] This is not to say that foundries using smaller wafers are necessarily obsolete; older foundries can be cheaper to operate, have higher yields for simple chips and still be productive.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] The industry was aiming to move from the state-of-the-art wafer size 300 mm (12 in) to 450 mm by 2018.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] In March 2014, Intel expected 450 mm deployment by 2020.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] But in 2016, corresponding joint research efforts were stopped.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] Additionally, there is a large push to completely automate the production of semiconductor chips from beginning to end.
[src:tsmc-process-node/semiconductor-fabrication-plant] This is often referred to as the "lights-out fab" concept.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Although the government of Taiwan is the largest individual shareholder, the majority of TSMC is owned by foreign investors.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In 2025, the company was ranked 38th in the *Forbes* Global 2000.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Taiwan's exports of integrated circuits amounted to $184 billion in 2022, nearly 25 percent of Taiwan's GDP.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC constitutes about 30 percent of the Taiwan Stock Exchange's main index.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company (TSMC) was established in 1987 as a joint venture between Taiwan’s government, the Industrial Technology Research Institute (ITRI), and private investors.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Morris Chang founded the company to commercialise semiconductor research originally developed at ITRI, becoming the world’s first dedicated semiconductor foundry.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] When Chang retired in 2018, after 31 years of TSMC leadership, Mark Liu became chairman and C.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] It has been listed on the Taiwan Stock Exchange since 1993; in 1997 it became the first Taiwanese company to be listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Since 1994, TSMC has had a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 17.4 percent in revenue and a CAGR of 16.1 percent in earnings.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Most fabless semiconductor companies such as AMD, Apple, ARM, Broadcom, Marvell, MediaTek, Qualcomm, and Nvidia are customers of TSMC, as are emerging companies such as Allwinner Technology, HiSilicon, Spectra7, and UNISOC.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Programmable logic device companies Xilinx and previously Altera also make or made use of TSMC's foundry services.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Some integrated device manufacturers that have their own fabrication facilities, such as Intel, NXP, STMicroelectronics, and Texas Instruments, outsource some of their production to TSMC.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC has a global capacity of about thirteen million 300 mm-equivalent wafers per year as of 2020 and produces chips for customers with process nodes from 2 microns to 3 nanometres.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC was the first foundry to market 7-nanometre and 5-nanometre (used by the 2020 Apple A14 and M1 SoCs, the MediaTek Dimensity 8100, and AMD Ryzen 7000 series processors) production capabilities, and the first to commercialise ASML's extreme ultraviolet (EUV) lithography technology in high volume.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In 1986, Li Kwoh-ting, representing the Executive Yuan, invited Morris Chang to serve as the president of the Industrial Technology Research Institute (ITRI) and offered him a blank cheque to build Taiwan's chip industry.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] At that time, the Taiwanese government wanted to develop its semiconductor industry, but its high investment and high risk nature made it difficult to find investors.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Texas Instruments and Intel turned down Chang.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Only Philips was willing to sign a joint venture contract with Taiwan to put up $58 million, transfer its production technology, and license intellectual property in exchange for a 27.6 percent stake in TSMC.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Alongside generous tax benefits, the Taiwanese government, through the National Development Fund, Executive Yuan, provided another 48.3 percent of the startup capital for TSMC.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] 20% of the capital was raised from eight private companies (ranging from Formosa Plastics Group’s 5%, CAPCO’s 5% to Taiyuan Textile’s 1%) which were owned by some of the island's wealthiest families, who owned firms that specialised in plastics, textiles, and chemicals.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] These wealthy Taiwanese were directly "asked" by the government to invest.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The rest of the 4.1% capital came from Taiwan's then ruling party’s investment arm: Kuomintang Central Investment Co.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] From the company's onset, TSMC operated primarily as a project of the Taiwanese state, as opposed to a completely private company.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Dykes, who left after a year and Morris Chang became the CEO.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Although Philips initially held a 27.5% stake in TSMC, its influence extended beyond financial investment.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In addition to capital, Philips played a crucial role by transferring semiconductor manufacturing technology, intellectual property, and patents to TSMC, enabling the company to scale more rapidly.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Philips also provided TSMC's first CEO, James E.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Dykes, who had previously worked at Philips North America.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] This partnership represented an early example of the "fab-light" strategy, as Philips gradually reduced its in-house semiconductor manufacturing and relied more on external foundries like TSMC.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Over the following decades, Philips steadily divested its stake in TSMC and shifted its primary focus to healthcare technology.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Since then, the company has continued to grow, albeit subject to the cycles of demand.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In 2011, the company planned to increase research and development expenditures by almost 39 percent to NT$50 billion to fend off growing competition.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The company also planned to expand capacity by 30 percent in 2011 to meet strong market demand.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In May 2014, TSMC's board of directors approved capital appropriations of US$568 million to increase and improve manufacturing capabilities after the company forecast higher than expected demand.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In August 2014, TSMC's board of directors approved additional capital appropriations of US$3.05 billion.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In 2011, it was reported that TSMC had begun trial production of the A5 SoC and A6 SoCs for Apple's iPad and iPhone devices.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] According to reports in May 2014, Apple sourced its A8 and A8X SoCs from TSMC.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Apple then sourced the A9 SoC with both TSMC and Samsung (to increase volume for iPhone 6S launch) and the A9X exclusively with TSMC, thus resolving the issue of sourcing a chip in two different microarchitecture sizes.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] As of 2014, Apple was TSMC's most important customer.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In October 2014, ARM and TSMC announced a new multi-year agreement for the development of ARM based 10 nm FinFET processors.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Over the objection of the Tsai Ing-wen administration, in March 2017, TSMC invested US$3 billion in Nanjing to develop a manufacturing subsidiary there.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In 2020, TSMC became the first semiconductor company in the world to sign up for the RE100 initiative, pledging to use 100 percent renewable energy by 2050.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC accounts for roughly 5 percent of the energy consumption in Taiwan, even exceeding that of the capital city Taipei.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] This initiative was thus expected to accelerate the transformation to renewable energy in the country.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] For 2020, TSMC had a net income of US$17.60 billion on a consolidated revenue of US$45.51 billion, an increase of 57.5 percent and 31.4 percent respectively from the 2019 level of US$11.18 billion net income and US$34.63 billion consolidated revenue.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Its market capitalisation was over $550 billion in April 2021.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC's revenue in the first quarter of 2020 reached US$10 billion, while its market capitalisation was US$254 billion.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC's market capitalisation reached a value of NT$1.9 trillion (US$63.4 billion) in December 2010.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] It was ranked 70th in the FT Global 500 2013 list of the world's most highly valued companies with a capitalisation of US$86.7 billion, while reaching US$110 billion in May 2014.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In March 2017, TSMC's market capitalisation surpassed that of semiconductor giant Intel for the first time, hitting NT$5.14 trillion (US$168.4 billion), with Intel's at US$165.7 billion.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] On 27 June 2020, TSMC briefly became the world's 10th most valuable company, with a market capitalisation of US$410 billion.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] To mitigate business risks in the event of war between Taiwan and the People's Republic of China, since the beginning of the 2020s, TSMC has expanded its geographic operations, opening new fabs in Japan and the United States, with further plans for expansion into Germany.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In July 2020, TSMC confirmed it would halt the shipment of silicon wafers to Chinese telecommunications equipment manufacturer Huawei and its subsidiary HiSilicon by 14 September.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In November 2020, officials in Phoenix, Arizona in the United States approved TSMC's plan to build a $12 billion chip plant in the city.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The decision to locate a plant in the US came after the Trump administration warned about the issues concerning the world's electronics made outside of the U.S.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In 2021, news reports claimed that the facility might be tripled to roughly a $35 billion investment with six factories.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In June 2021, following nearly a year of public controversy surrounding its COVID-19 vaccine shortage, with only about 10 percent of its 23.5 million population vaccinated; Taiwan agreed to allow TSMC and Foxconn to jointly negotiate purchasing COVID-19 vaccines on its behalf.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In July 2021, BioNTech's Chinese sales agent Fosun Pharma announced that the two technology manufacturers had reached an agreement to purchase 10 million BioNTech COVID-19 vaccines from Germany.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC and Foxconn pledged to each buy five million doses for up to $175 million, for donation to Taiwan's vaccination programme.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Due to the 2020–2023 global semiconductor shortage, Taiwanese competitor United Microelectronics raised prices approximately 7–9 percent, and prices for TSMC's more mature processors were raised by about 20 percent.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In November 2021, TSMC and Sony announced that TSMC would be establishing a new subsidiary named Japan Advanced Semiconductor Manufacturing (JASM) in Kumamoto, Japan.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The subsidiary manufactures 22- and 28-nanometre processes.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The initial investment was approximately $7 billion, with Sony investing approximately $500 million for a less than 20 percent stake.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Construction of the fabrication plant started in 2022, with production beginning two years later in 2024.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In February 2022, TSMC, Sony Semiconductor Solutions, and Denso announced that Denso would take a more than 10 percent equity stake in JASM with a US$0.35 billion investment, amid a scarcity of chips for automobiles.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC will also enhance JASM's capabilities with 12/16 nanometre FinFET process technology in addition to the previously announced 22/28 nanometre process and increase monthly production capacity from 45,000 to 55,000 12-inch wafers.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The total capital expenditure for JASM's Kumamoto fab is estimated to be approximately US$8.6 billion.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The Japanese government wants JASM to supply essential chips to Japan's electronic device makers and auto companies as trade friction between the United States and China threatens to disrupt supply chains.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The fab is expected to directly create about 1,700 high-tech professional jobs.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In July 2022, TSMC announced the company had posted a record profit in the second quarter, with net income up 76.4 percent year-over-year.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The company saw steady growth in the automotive and data centre sectors with some weakness in the consumer market.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Some of the capital expenditures are projected to be pushed up to 2023.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In the third quarter of 2022, Berkshire Hathaway disclosed purchase of 60 million shares in TSMC, acquiring a $4.1 billion stake, making it one of its largest holdings in a technology company.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] However, Berkshire sold off 86.2 percent of its stake by the next quarter citing geopolitical tensions as a factor.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In February 2024, TSMC shares hit a record high, with the high on the trading day reaching NT$709 and closing at NT$697 (+8%).
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] This was influenced by the increase in the price target on chip designer Nvidia.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC currently manufactures 3-nanometre chips and plans to start 2-nanometre mass production in 2025.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] It is included in the FTSE4Good Index, being the only Asian company in the top ten.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In October 2024, TSMC informed the United States Department of Commerce about a potential breach of export controls in which one of its most advanced chips was sent to Huawei via another company with ties to the Chinese government.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In June 2025, TSMC announced the establishment of the TSMC-UTokyo Lab (TSMC-University of Tokyo Laboratory), marking its first joint research laboratory with an overseas university.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In August 2025, TSMC reported that two current employees and six former employees had illegally acquired trade secrets related to the company's leading 2nm process.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] One of them went on to work for Tokyo Electron, a partner of Japan's semiconductor effort Rapidus, but has since been terminated.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] A number of suspects have been arrested by Taiwanese authorities.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In January 2026, reported a 35% increase in fourth-quarter profit.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] This is higher than previous estimates, hitting a fresh record as demand for artificial intelligence chips remained strong.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] On 26 August 2019, GlobalFoundries filed several patent infringement lawsuits against TSMC in the US and Germany claiming that TSMC's 7 nm, 10 nm, 12 nm, 16 nm, and 28 nm nodes infringed 16 of its patents.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] GlobalFoundries named twenty defendants.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC said that it was confident that the allegations were baseless.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] On 1 October 2019, TSMC filed patent infringement lawsuits against GlobalFoundries in the US, Germany and Singapore, claiming that GlobalFoundries' 12 nm, 14 nm, 22 nm, 28 nm and 40 nm nodes infringed 25 of its patents.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] On 29 October 2019, TSMC and GlobalFoundries announced a resolution to the dispute, agreeing to a life-of-patents cross-licence for all of their existing semiconductor patents and new patents for the next 10 years.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC and the rest of the foundry industry are exposed to the cyclical industrial dynamics of the semiconductor industry.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC must ensure its production capacity to meet strong customer demand during upturns; however, during downturns, it must contend with excess capacity because of weak demand and the high fixed costs associated with its manufacturing facilities.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] As a result, the company's financial results tend to fluctuate with a cycle time of a few years.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] This is more apparent in earnings than revenues because of the general trend of revenue and capacity growth.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC's business has generally also been seasonal, with a peak in Q3 and a low in Q1.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In 2014, TSMC was at the forefront of the foundry industry for high-performance, low-power applications, leading major smartphone chip companies, such as Qualcomm, Mediatek, and Apple, to place an increasing amount of orders.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] For most of 2014, TSMC saw a continuing increase in revenues due to increased demand, primarily due to chips for smartphone applications.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC raised its financial guidance in March 2014 and posted 'unseasonably strong' first-quarter results.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] For Q2 2014, revenues came in at NT$183 billion, with 28 nm technology business growing more than 30 percent from the previous quarter.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] However, monthly sales for 2014 peaked in October, decreasing by 10 percent in November due to cautious inventory adjustment actions taken by some of its customers.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In 2019, TSMC was ranked fourth in the MEMS field, behind leader Silex Microsystems.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In 2021, TSMC was ranked third in the MEMS field.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Around 56 percent of TSMC shares are held by the general public and around 38 percent are held by institutions.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC's N7+ is the first commercially available extreme-ultraviolet lithographic process in the semiconductor industry.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] It uses ultraviolet patterning and enables more acute circuits to be implemented on the silicon.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] N7+ offers a 15–20 percent higher transistor density and 10 percent reduction in power consumption than previous technology.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The N7 achieved the fastest ever volume time to market, faster than 10 nm and 16 nm.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The N5 iteration doubles transistor density and improves performance by an additional 15 percent.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In late 2022, TSMC began volume production of its 3 nm process (N3), which provides up to a 70% increase in logic density and a 15% speed improvement over the 5 nm generation.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] By late 2025, the company transitioned to its 2 nm technology (N2), marking a major architectural shift from FinFET to Gate-All-Around (GAA) nanosheet transistors.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The N2 node offers a 10 to 15% performance boost or a 25 to 30% reduction in power consumption compared to the enhanced 3 nm (N3E) process, while increasing chip density by more than 15%.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] It also offers "design for manufacturing" (DFM) customer services.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In press publications, these processes will often be referenced, for example, for the mobile variant, simply by 7*nmFinFET* or even more briefly by 7FF.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] At the beginning of 2019, TSMC was advertising N7+, N7, and N6 as its leading edge technologies.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] As of June 2020, TSMC is the manufacturer selected for production of Apple's 5 nanometre ARM processors, as "the company plans to eventually transition the entire Mac lineup to its Arm-based processors, including the priciest desktop computers".
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In July 2021, both Apple and Intel were reported to be testing their proprietary chip designs with TSMC's 3 nm production.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The investment of US$9.4 billion to build its third 300mm wafer fabrication facility in Central Taiwan Science Park (Fab 15) was originally announced in 2010.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The facility was expected to manufacture over 100,000 wafers a month and generate US$5 billion per year of revenue.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC has continued to expand advanced 28 nm manufacturing capacity at Fab 15.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] On 12 January 2011, TSMC announced the acquisition of land from Powerchip Semiconductor for NT$2.9 billion (US$96 million) to build two additional 300mm fabs (Fab 12B) to cope with increasing global demand.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In August 2023, TSMC committed €3.5 billion to a €10+ billion factory in Dresden, Germany.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The plant is subsidised with €5 billion from the German government.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Three European companies (Robert Bosch GmbH, Infineon Technologies, and NXP Semiconductors) invested in the plant in return for a 10 percent share each.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The resulting joint venture with TSMC is named European Semiconductor Manufacturing Company (ESMC).
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The factory is planned to be fully operational in 2029 with a monthly capacity of 40,000 12-inch wafers.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Denso and Toyota have also invested in the company and are minor shareholders.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The first factory (Fab 23) in Kikuyo, began commercial operations in December 2024 and produces 12-, 22-, and 28-nanometre processes.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] Fab 23 cost US$8.6 billion to build, with 476 billion yen subsidised by the Ministry of Economy, Trade and Industry (METI).
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The second factory, currently under construction adjacent to Fab 23 as of January 2025, will produce 6-nanometre and 12-nanometre processes.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] This factory is estimated to cost US$13.9 billion, with 732 billion yen funded by the METI.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In 2020, TSMC announced a planned fab in Phoenix, Arizona with a $12 billion investment which intended to begin production by 2024.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] At launch it was the most advanced fab in the United States.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC claimed the plant will create 1,900 full-time jobs.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In December 2022, TSMC announced its plans to triple its investment in the Arizona plants in response to the growing tensions between the US and China and the supply chain disruption that has led to chip shortages.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In that same month, TSMC stated that it was running into major cost issues, because the cost of construction of buildings and facilities in the US is four to five times what an identical plant would cost in Taiwan, as well as difficulty finding qualified personnel.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] These additional production costs will increase the cost of TSMC's chips made in the US to at least 50 percent more than the cost of chips made in Taiwan.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In July 2023 TSMC warned that US talent was insufficient, so Taiwanese workers will need to be brought in for a limited time, and that the chip factory will not be operational until 2025.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In September 2023, an analyst said the chips will still need to be sent back to Taiwan for packaging.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In January 2024, TSMC chairman Liu again warned that Arizona lacked workers with the specialised skills to hire and that TSMC's second Arizona plant likely will not start volume production of advanced chips until 2027 or 2028.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In November 2024, the Commerce Department finalised the binding $6.6 billion CHIPS Act award — the first major award completed under the $52.7 billion programme.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC also agreed to use its most advanced "A16" manufacturing technology in Arizona and committed to forgo stock buybacks for five years under an "upside sharing agreement" with the US government.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In July 2025, Wei indicated that TSMC would speed up its production timelines toward the completion of a "gigafab" cluster totalling six facilities after an additional $100 billion investment in Arizona.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC Washington is a subsidiary of TSMC based in Camas, Washington, 32 km (20 mi) outside Portland, Oregon.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The 105 ha (260 acres) campus contains a 9.3 ha (23 acres) complex consisting of a 12,000 m2 (130,000 sq ft) 200mm wafer fabrication plant.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC Washington (originally known as WaferTech) was established in June 1996 as a joint venture between TSMC, Altera, Analog Devices, and ISSI.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The companies along with minor individual investors placed US$1.2 billion into this venture, which was at the time the single largest startup investment in the state of Washington.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The facility started production in July 1998 with its first product being a 0.35 micrometre part for Altera.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC bought out the stake of the other partners in 2000, turning the company into a fully owned subsidiary of TSMC.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] As of 2024, the facility employs 1100 workers and supports node sizes of 0.35, 0.30, 0.25, 0.22, 0.18, and 0.16 micrometres, with an emphasis on embedded flash process technology.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC's operations consume a large amount of power and water and thus have significant environmental impact.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] TSMC pledged to have net-zero emissions by 2050 and to power all global operations with 100% renewable energy within that same timeframe.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] The company has also invested in water conservation technologies, including high-efficiency wastewater recycling systems capable of reclaiming over 85% of water used in fabrication processes.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In 2024, TSMC reportedly consumed over 150,000 tons of water per day in Hsinchu City, approximately 10% of the city's water supply.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] In July 2020, TSMC signed a 20-year deal with Ørsted to buy the entire production of two offshore wind farms under development off Taiwan's west coast.
[src:tsmc-process-node/tsmc] At the time of its signing, it was the world's largest corporate green energy order ever made.
